Charles Augustus Lindbergh (February 4, 1902 – August 26, 1974) was an American aviator, military officer, and author. He is most famously remembered for achieving the first nonstop solo flight from [New York](/New_York_(state)) to [Paris](/Paris) on May 20–21, 1927. This remarkable feat, spanning 3,600 miles (5,800 km) and lasting over 33 hours, was accomplished in his custom-built aircraft, the [Spirit of St. Louis](/Spirit_of_St._Louis). The flight was undertaken to compete for the $25,000 [Orteig Prize](/Orteig_Prize), which had been established for the first successful nonstop transatlantic journey between the two cities. While not the absolute first transatlantic flight, as the [Alcock and Brown flight](/Transatlantic_flight_of_Alcock_and_Brown) had occurred previously, Lindbergh's was the first solo crossing of the Atlantic and, at that time, the longest continuous flight by nearly 2,000 miles (3,200 km), setting a new world record for flight distance. This achievement propelled Lindbergh to international fame and is considered one of the most significant flights in aviation history, heralding a new era of [air transportation](/International_flight) and global connectivity. Beyond his aviation triumphs, Lindbergh later became a prominent figure in political activism, advocating for a non-interventionist stance during [World War II](/World_War_II), which led to accusations of Nazi sympathy.

Lindbergh spent his formative years primarily in [Little Falls, Minnesota](/Little_Falls,_Minnesota), and [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). His father, [Charles August Lindbergh](/Charles_August_Lindbergh), served as a U.S. Congressman. In 1924, Lindbergh enlisted as a cadet in the [U.S. Army Air Service](/United_States_Army_Air_Service). The following year, he began his career as an [air mail](/Air_mail) pilot for the [U.S. Air Mail](/U.S._Air_Mail) service in the [Greater St. Louis](/Greater_St._Louis) area, a period during which he meticulously prepared for his ambitious transatlantic flight. For his groundbreaking 1927 flight, President [Calvin Coolidge](/Calvin_Coolidge) bestowed upon him both the [Distinguished Flying Cross](/Distinguished_Flying_Cross_(United_States)) and the [Medal of Honor](/Medal_of_Honor), the highest military decorations in the United States. He was also promoted to [colonel](/Colonel) in the [U.S. Army Air Corps Reserve](/U.S._Army_Air_Corps_Reserve) and received France's highest order of merit, the [Legion of Honor](/Legion_of_Honour). Lindbergh's accomplishment ignited a global surge of interest in [flight training](/Flight_training), [commercial aviation](/Commercial_aviation), and [air mail](/Air_mail) services, sparking what became known as the "[Lindbergh Boom](/Lindbergh_Boom)" and fundamentally transforming the aviation industry.

[Time](/Time_(magazine)) magazine recognized Lindbergh as its inaugural [Man of the Year](/Time_Person_of_the_Year) for 1927. In 1929, President [Herbert Hoover](/Herbert_Hoover) appointed him to the [National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics](/National_Advisory_Committee_for_Aeronautics). Later, in 1931, Lindbergh collaborated with French surgeon [Alexis Carrel](/Alexis_Carrel) on the development of the first [perfusion pump](/Perfusion), a device that laid the groundwork for future advancements in [cardiac surgery](/Cardiac_surgery) and [organ transplantation](/Organ_transplantation).

The Lindbergh family experienced a profound personal tragedy on March 1, 1932, when their infant son, Charles Jr., was [kidnapped and murdered](/Lindbergh_kidnapping). This event, dubbed the "[crime of the century](/Crime_of_the_century)", prompted the U.S. Congress to enact the [Federal Kidnapping Act](/Federal_Kidnapping_Act), criminalizing kidnapping across state lines. The intense public scrutiny and hysteria surrounding the case led the Lindberghs to seek refuge in Europe from late 1935 until 1939.

In the years leading up to the United States' entry into [World War II](/World_War_II), Lindbergh became a vocal proponent of [non-interventionism](/Non-interventionism). His public statements on issues of race and his perceived association with Nazi Germany led to widespread accusations of Nazi sympathy. While Lindbergh consistently denied supporting the Nazis and publicly condemned their actions on several occasions, his close ties and numerous interactions with them throughout the 1930s fueled the controversy. He was a prominent supporter of the [isolationist](/Isolationist) [America First Committee](/America_First_Committee), and resigned his commission in the U.S. Army Air Corps Reserve in April 1941 after President [Franklin Roosevelt](/Franklin_Roosevelt) publicly criticized his views. In September 1941, Lindbergh delivered a significant address, "Speech on Neutrality," articulating his arguments against greater American involvement in the war.

Following the [Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor](/Japanese_attack_on_Pearl_Harbor) and Germany's declaration of war on the United States, Lindbergh actively supported the American war effort. Despite being denied active duty, he flew 50 combat missions in the [Pacific Theater](/Pacific_Theater_of_World_War_II) as a civilian consultant, unofficially credited with shooting down an enemy aircraft. In 1954, President [Dwight Eisenhower](/Dwight_Eisenhower) reinstated his commission and promoted him to [brigadier general](/Brigadier_general) in the [U.S. Air Force Reserve](/Air_Force_Reserve_Command). In his later years, Lindbergh achieved recognition as a [Pulitzer Prize](/Pulitzer_Prize_for_Biography_or_Autobiography)-winning author, an international explorer, and an environmentalist. He played a role in establishing [national parks](/National_parks) in the U.S. and advocated for the protection of [endangered species](/Endangered_species) and indigenous populations in the [Philippines](/Tasaday) and [east Africa](/Maasai_people). Lindbergh passed away in 1974 at the age of 72 in [Kipahulu, Hawaii](/Kipahulu,_Hawaii), from [lymphoma](/Lymphoma).

### Early life

Lindbergh was born in [Detroit](/Detroit), Michigan, on February 4, 1902. His childhood was largely spent in [Little Falls, Minnesota](/Little_Falls,_Minnesota), and [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.). He was the only child of [Charles August Lindbergh](/Charles_August_Lindbergh) (born Carl Månsson), who had [emigrated from Sweden](/Swedish_Americans) as an infant, and [Evangeline Lodge Land Lindbergh](/Evangeline_Lodge_Land_Lindbergh) of Detroit. Lindbergh had three older paternal half-sisters from his father's previous marriage. His parents separated in 1909 when he was seven years old.

His father, a [U.S. Congressman](/United_States_Congress) from 1907 to 1917, was one of the few members of Congress to oppose the [entry of the U.S. into World War I](/American_entry_into_World_I), though his term concluded a month before the [House of Representatives](/United_States_House_of_Representatives) voted to [declare war on Germany](/United_States_declaration_of_war_on_Germany_(1917)). Lindbergh's mother was a chemistry teacher, first at [Cass Technical High School](/Cass_Technical_High_School) in Detroit and later at [Little Falls High School](/Little_Falls,_Minnesota), from which Charles graduated in June 1918. Throughout his childhood and teenage years, Lindbergh attended over a dozen schools across the country, including the Force School and [Sidwell Friends School](/Sidwell_Friends_School) in Washington, D.C., and [Redondo Union High School](/Redondo_Union_High_School) in [Redondo Beach, California](/Redondo_Beach,_California). He enrolled in the College of Engineering at the [University of Wisconsin–Madison](/University_of_Wisconsin%E2%80%93Madison) in late 1920 but left during his sophomore year.

### Early aviation career

From a young age, Lindbergh displayed a keen interest in mechanics, particularly in his family's [Saxon Six](/Saxon_(automobile)) and later his [Excelsior](/Excelsior_Motor_Manufacturing_%26_Supply_Company) motorbike. While pursuing a degree in [mechanical engineering](/Mechanical_engineering) at the university, he became captivated by aviation, despite having had no prior direct experience with aircraft. In February 1922, after leaving college, Lindbergh enrolled in the Nebraska Aircraft Corporation's flying school in [Lincoln](/Lincoln,_Nebraska). His first flight was on April 9, 1922, as a passenger in a two-seat [Lincoln Standard "Tourabout"](/Standard_J) biplane trainer piloted by [Otto Timm](/Otto_Timm).

Though he commenced formal flying lessons shortly thereafter, Lindbergh was unable to solo due to financial constraints preventing him from posting the required damage bond. To gain flight experience and fund further training, Lindbergh left Lincoln in June and spent several months [barnstorming](/Barnstorming) across [Nebraska](/Nebraska), [Kansas](/Kansas), [Colorado](/Colorado), [Wyoming](/Wyoming), and [Montana](/Montana). During this period, he worked as a [wing walker](/Wing_walking) and [parachutist](/Parachuting), and briefly as an airplane mechanic at the [Billings, Montana, municipal airport](/Billings_Logan_International_Airport).

"Daredevil Lindbergh" in a re-engined Standard J-1, c. 1925. The aircraft in this photograph is frequently misidentified as a Curtiss "Jenny".

Lindbergh’s return to flying and his first solo flight occurred in May 1923 at [Souther Field](/Jimmy_Carter_Regional_Airport) in [Americus, Georgia](/Americus,_Georgia). He purchased a surplus World War I [Curtiss JN-4 "Jenny"](/Curtiss_JN-4) biplane for $500. Despite a six-month hiatus from flying, Lindbergh, having secretly prepared himself, took to the air alone after a brief refresher session with another pilot at the field. He then embarked on his first solo cross-country flight to [Montgomery, Alabama](/Montgomery,_Alabama). For the remainder of 1923, Lindbergh continued barnstorming under the moniker "Daredevil Lindbergh," piloting his own aircraft and making his first night flight near [Lake Village, Arkansas](/Lake_Village,_Arkansas).

Lindbergh as a young 2nd Lt., March 1925.

While barnstorming in [Lone Rock, Wisconsin](/Lone_Rock,_Wisconsin), Lindbergh twice assisted a local physician by flying him across the [Wisconsin River](/Wisconsin_River) for emergency calls, navigating flood conditions. His flying was not without incident; he broke his propeller multiple times and was grounded for a week after an accident in [Glencoe, Minnesota](/Glencoe,_Minnesota), while flying his father to a campaign stop. In October, he sold his Jenny in [Iowa](/Iowa) and returned to Lincoln, where he partnered with Leon Klink to continue barnstorming across the South in Klink's Curtiss JN-4C "Canuck." During this period, Lindbergh also experienced an engine failure shortly after takeoff in [Pensacola, Florida](/Pensacola,_Florida), but managed to repair the aircraft himself.

After parting ways with Klink in [San Antonio](/San_Antonio), Texas, Lindbergh reported to [Brooks Field](/Brooks_City-Base) on March 19, 1924, for a year of military flight training with the [United States Army Air Service](/United_States_Army_Air_Service), continuing his training at nearby [Kelly Field](/Kelly_Field_Annex). His most significant aviation accident occurred on March 5, 1925, just eight days before graduation, when a mid-air collision with another Army [S.E.5](/Royal_Aircraft_Factory_S.E.5) during aerial combat maneuvers forced him to parachute to safety. Lindbergh graduated first in his class of 104 cadets in March 1925, earning his Army pilot's wings and a commission as a [second lieutenant](/Second_lieutenant) in the [Air Service Reserve Corps](/Military_reserve_force).

Lindbergh later reflected that this training period was pivotal in shaping him into a focused, goal-oriented individual and a skilled aviator. However, with no immediate need for additional active-duty pilots, Lindbergh returned to civilian aviation. He continued barnstorming and working as a [flight instructor](/Flight_instructor), while also maintaining his reserve status by flying with the [110th Observation Squadron](/110th_Bomb_Squadron) of the Missouri [National Guard](/National_Guard_of_the_United_States). He was promoted to [first lieutenant](/First_Lieutenant) on December 7, 1925, and to captain in July 1926.

### Air mail pilot

In October 1925, Lindbergh was hired by the [Robertson Aircraft Corporation](/Robertson_Aircraft_Corporation) (RAC) at [Lambert-St. Louis Flying Field](/Lambert-St._Louis_International_Airport) in Anglum, Missouri. He was tasked with establishing and then serving as chief pilot for the new [Contract Air Mail](/Airmails_of_the_United_States) Route #2 (CAM-2). This route covered 278 miles (447 km) between [St. Louis](/St._Louis,_Missouri) and [Chicago](/Chicago), with intermediate stops in [Springfield](/Springfield,_Illinois) and [Peoria, Illinois](/Peoria,_Illinois). Lindbergh, along with three other RAC pilots, flew the mail using a fleet of four modified surplus [de Havilland DH-4s](/Airco_DH.4).

On April 13, 1926, Lindbergh formally took the [United States Post Office Department](/United_States_Post_Office_Department)'s Oath of Mail Messengers, and two days later, initiated service on the new route. During his tenure, Lindbergh experienced two instances where challenging conditions forced him to bail out upon night approach to [Chicago](/Chicago). These incidents were attributed to a combination of adverse weather, mechanical failures, and [fuel exhaustion](/Fuel_starvation), but he landed safely on both occasions. In mid-February 1927, Lindbergh traveled to [San Diego](/San_Diego), California, to oversee the design and construction of the [Spirit of St. Louis](/Spirit_of_St._Louis).

