### Writings

In addition to "[WE"](/%22WE%22_(1927_book)) and *The Spirit of St. Louis*, Lindbergh authored numerous works on science, technology, nationalism, war, materialism, and values. His published books include *The Culture of Organs* (with [Dr. Alexis Carrel](/Alexis_Carrel)) (1938), *Of Flight and Life* (1948), *The Wartime Journals of Charles A. Lindbergh* (1970), *Boyhood on the Upper Mississippi* (1972), and his unfinished *Autobiography of Values* (published posthumously in 1978).

### In popular culture

#### Literature

Beyond numerous biographies, such as A. Scott Berg's acclaimed 1998 bestseller [Lindbergh](/Lindbergh_(book)), Lindbergh's life and persona influenced or served as the basis for characters in various fictional works. Shortly after his famous flight, the [Stratemeyer Syndicate](/Stratemeyer_Syndicate) launched the [Ted Scott Flying Stories](/Ted_Scott_Flying_Stories) series (1927–1943) for young readers, authored under the [nom de plume](/Pen_name) "[Franklin W. Dixon](/Franklin_W._Dixon)". The protagonist, Ted Scott, mirrored Lindbergh, notably replicating the solo flight to Paris in the series' inaugural volume, *Over the Ocean to Paris* (1927). [Agatha Christie]'s novel *Murder on the Orient Express* (1934) and its 1974 film adaptation [Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)](/Murder_on_the_Orient_Express_(1974_film)) commence with a fictionalized depiction of the [Lindbergh kidnapping](/Lindbergh_kidnapping).

Several [alternate history](/Alternate_history) novels explore Lindbergh's alleged Nazi sympathies and non-interventionist stance during the early years of [World War II](/World_War_II). In [Daniel Easterman]'s *K is for Killing* (1997), a fictional Lindbergh assumes the presidency of a fascist [United States](/United_States). [Philip Roth]'s novel [The Plot Against America](/The_Plot_Against_America) (2004) presents an alternative history where Lindbergh defeats [Franklin Delano Roosevelt](/Franklin_Delano_Roosevelt) in the [1940](/1940_United_States_presidential_election) presidential election and aligns the United States with [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany).

[Robert Harris]'s novel [Fatherland](/Fatherland_(novel)) (1992) posits an alternate reality where the Nazis achieved victory in the war, the United States defeated [Japan](/Japan), and [Adolf Hitler](/Adolf_Hitler) and President [Joseph Kennedy](/Joseph_Kennedy) negotiated peace terms, with Lindbergh serving as the [US Ambassador to Germany](/US_Ambassador_to_Germany). [Jo Walton]'s novel [Farthing](/Farthing_(novel)) (2006) explores an alternate history where the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom) made peace with Nazi Germany in 1941, Japan never attacked [Pearl Harbor](/Pearl_Harbor), preventing U.S. involvement in the war, and Lindbergh, as president, pursues closer economic ties with the [Greater East Asian Co-Prosperity Sphere](/Greater_East_Asian_Co-Prosperity_Sphere).

In [Back in the USSA](/Back_in_the_USSA) by [Eugene Byrne](/Eugene_Byrne) and [Kim Newman](/Kim_Newman) (1997), Lindbergh is depicted as a member of the Revolutionary Fraternity Squadron, a group of heroic aviators undertaking propaganda tours across the USSA, portrayed as one of the more honorable members.

#### Film and television

• Lindbergh has been the subject of numerous documentaries, including *Charles A. Lindbergh* (1927), a British film by De Forest Phonofilm; *40,000 Miles with Lindbergh* (1928), featuring Lindbergh himself; and *The American Experience—Lindbergh: The Shocking, Turbulent Life of America's Lone Eagle* (1988).

• The 1942 [MGM](/Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer) film *[Keeper of the Flame](/Keeper_of_the_Flame_(film))*, starring [Katharine Hepburn](/Katharine_Hepburn) and [Spencer Tracy](/Spencer_Tracy), features Hepburn as the widow of a national hero reminiscent of Lindbergh.

• In the major motion picture *[The Spirit of St. Louis](/The_Spirit_of_St._Louis_(film))* (1957), directed by [Billy Wilder](/Billy_Wilder), Lindbergh was portrayed by [James Stewart](/James_Stewart), an admirer of Lindbergh and a World War II aviator himself. The film primarily focuses on Lindbergh's record-breaking 1927 flight. Prior to Stewart's casting, [John Kerr](/John_Kerr_(actor)) declined the role due to Lindbergh's alleged pro-Nazi sympathies.

• In 1976, [Buzz Kulik]'s television movie *[The Lindbergh Kidnapping Case](/The_Lindbergh_Kidnapping_Case)*, featuring [Anthony Hopkins](/Anthony_Hopkins) as [Richard Hauptmann](/Richard_Hauptmann), premiered on [NBC](/NBC).

• Lindbergh was the subject of prolific director [Orson Welles]'s final film project in 1984, *[The Spirit of Charles Lindbergh](/The_Spirit_of_Charles_Lindbergh)*, in which Welles discusses the human spirit while quoting Lindbergh's journal. Although never intended for public release, a brief clip is featured in Vassili Slovic's 1995 documentary *Orson Welles: the One-Man Band*.

• The 2020 [HBO](/HBO) alternate history miniseries *[The Plot Against America](/The_Plot_Against_America_(miniseries))*, based on Philip Roth's novel of the same name, features actor Ben Cole as a fictionalized President Lindbergh following his defeat of Roosevelt in 1940. The series depicts Lindbergh as a [xenophobic](/Xenophobic) populist with significant ties to Nazi Germany.

• [Charles Lindbergh "Chuck" McGill](/Chuck_McGill), a fictional character in the television series [Better Call Saul](/Better_Call_Saul) (2015–2022), was named in honor of Lindbergh.

#### Music

Within days of his flight, numerous popular songs celebrating Lindbergh and the Spirit of St. Louis were published by [Tin Pan Alley](/Tin_Pan_Alley) publishers, including "[Lindbergh (The Eagle of the U.S.A.)](/Lindbergh_(The_Eagle_of_the_U.S.A.))" by Howard Johnson and [Al Sherman](/Al_Sherman), and "[Lucky Lindy!](/Lucky_Lindy!)" by [L. Wolfe Gilbert](/L._Wolfe_Gilbert) and Abel Baer. Over the two years following Lindbergh's flight, the U.S. Copyright Office registered three hundred applications for songs about Lindbergh. [Tony Randall](/Tony_Randall) revived "Lucky Lindy" for his 1967 album of [Jazz Age](/Jazz_Age) and [Depression](/Great_Depression)-era songs, titled *Vo Vo De Oh Doe*.

While the precise origin of the name "Lindy Hop" is debated, it is widely acknowledged that Lindbergh's 1927 flight contributed to its popularization. Following "Lucky Lindy's" transatlantic journey, the Lindy Hop became a fashionable dance, and songs referencing the "Lindbergh Hop" were quickly released.

In 1929, [Bertolt Brecht](/Bertolt_Brecht) wrote a cantata titled *Der Lindberghflug* (Lindbergh's Flight), with music by [Kurt Weill](/Kurt_Weill) and [Paul Hindemith](/Paul_Hindemith). Due to Lindbergh's perceived Nazi sympathies, Brecht removed all direct references to him in 1950 and renamed the work *Der Ozeanflug* (The Flight Across the Ocean).

In the early 1940s, [Woody Guthrie](/Woody_Guthrie) composed "Lindbergh" or "Mister Charlie Lindbergh," a song criticizing Lindbergh's association with the [America First Committee](/America_First_Committee) and his suspected sympathies towards Nazi Germany.

#### Postage stamps

•

Lindbergh's numerous flights in the [Spirit of Saint Louis](/Spirit_of_Saint_Louis) were depicted on a 10¢ U.S. [Air Mail stamp](/Airmails_of_the_United_States), issued on June 11, 1927 (C-10).

Scott C-10 and #1710 with May 20, 1977 First Day of Issue CDS.

Lindbergh and the Spirit of St. Louis have been honored on various postage stamps worldwide over eight decades, including three issued by the United States. Less than three weeks after the flight, the [U.S. Post Office Department](/United_States_Post_Office_Department) released a 10-cent "Lindbergh Air Mail" stamp on June 11, 1927, featuring engraved illustrations of the Spirit of St. Louis and a map of its route from New York to Paris. This was the first U.S. stamp to bear the name of a living person. On May 20, 1977, the 50th anniversary of the flight from [Roosevelt Field](/Roosevelt_Field_(airport)), a 13-cent commemorative stamp depicting the Spirit over the Atlantic Ocean was issued. On May 28, 1998, a 32¢ stamp titled "Lindbergh Flies Atlantic," featuring Lindbergh and the Spirit, was issued as part of the [Celebrate the Century](/Celebrate_the_Century) stamp series.

#### Other

During World War II, Lindbergh was frequently targeted by [Dr. Seuss]'s early political cartoons, published in the New York magazine [PM](/PM_(newspaper)). Seuss criticized Lindbergh's isolationism, antisemitism, and alleged Nazi sympathies.

The [Spirit of St. Louis](/Spirit_of_St._Louis) is featured in the opening sequence of *[Star Trek: Enterprise](/Star_Trek:_Enterprise)* (2001–2005).

The St. Louis-based airline [GoJet Airlines](/GoJet_Airlines) uses the callsign "Lindbergh" in honor of Charles Lindbergh.

The aeronautically themed Hotel Charles Lindbergh at the German theme park [Phantasialand](/Phantasialand) was named after Lindbergh.

